## How a Focus Timer Works

A focus timer has three components:

1. **Duration** — the length of the focused work interval (25, 45, 52, or 90 minutes)
2. **Signal** — an alert (sound, visual, or haptic) when the interval ends
3. **Recovery** — a defined break period before the next interval

The timer creates a contract: for the duration of the session, you work only on the designated task. No context switching, no checking messages, no interruptions. When the timer ends, the contract is complete.

## Physical vs. Digital Focus Timers

**Physical timers** (kitchen timers, the Time Timer visual clock) have one advantage: the physical act of winding or setting the timer creates a ritual that signals the start of focused work. They have no screens and cannot distract you.

**Digital timers** (browser apps, dedicated apps) add session logging, streak tracking, and analytics — converting individual sessions into a long-term tracking system. Focus Clock, for example, logs every session automatically, building a heatmap of your focus habit over time.

## Why Focus Timers Reduce Procrastination

The primary mechanism is reducing the psychological commitment horizon. The question "can I focus on this for an hour?" generates resistance. The question "can I focus for 25 minutes?" generates much less. Focus timers make starting easier by shrinking the apparent commitment to a manageable interval.

This effect is related to what behavioral economists call "temporal myopia" — humans overweight immediate costs (starting a difficult task) relative to future rewards (finishing it). A focus timer shifts the psychology by making the session feel finite and achievable.

